'''Kristina Stefanova Sandulova''' ({{lang-bg|<U+041A><U+0440><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0438><U+043D><U+0430> <U+0421><U+0442><U+0435><U+0444><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430> <U+0421><U+0430><U+043D><U+0434><U+0443><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>}}, born {{birth date|1978|5|11}} in [[Sofia]], [[Bulgaria]]), is a concert pianist, Bulgarian by birth and Dutch by nationality.  She emigrated to the Netherlands in 2001, and currently resides in [[Vienna]], Austria.  She has an international concert career.
[[File:Kristina small.jpg|thumb|Kristina Sandulova]]
Sandulova is the daughter of the renowned Bulgarian composer [[Julia Tsenova|prof. Julia Tsenova]].

==Biography==

Kristina Sandulova began her piano studies with her mother, the composer [[Julia Tsenova]], having her first public performance at the age of six, at the [[National Palace of Culture| National Palace of Culture (<U+041D><U+0414><U+041A>)]]. She later studied at the [[National Academy of Music (Bulgaria)|National Academy of Music <U+201C>Pancho Vladigerov<U+201D>]] under the supervision of prof. Stella Dimitrova-Maistrova.<ref>[http://www.nma.bg/en/structure/?id=43  National Academy of Music <U+201C>Prof. Pancho Vladigerov<U+201D> <U+2013> Stella Dimitrova-Maistrova]</ref> In 2001 she received a grant from the <U+201C>Stichting Labbert<U+00E9>-Hoedemaker Fonds<U+201D> in order to continue her studies in the Netherlands. There Sandulova studied with [[:nl:Paul Komen|Paul Komen]], [[Geoffrey Douglas Madge|Geoffrey Madge]] and [[:nl:Kl<U+00E1>ra W<U+00FC>rtz|Kl<U+00E1>ra W<U+00FC>rtz]] at the [[Prins Claus Conservatorium]], the [[Royal Conservatory of The Hague]] and the [[Utrechts Conservatorium|Conservatory of Utrecht]], respectively.

Currently Sandulova resides in [[Vienna]], Austria, and has an international concert career, having performed in the Netherlands, Austria, Germany, Irelend, Bulgaria, Norway, Iceland, Japan and the United Kingdom. She is also the founder of the <U+201C>Julia Tsenova Music & Arts Tribute<U+201D>, a concert series dedicated to the memory of her mother, [[Julia Tsenova]], which began as a joint initiative with artist-composer Joseph Johannes Visser.<ref>[http://www.josephjohnvisser.nl/ Homepage of Joseph Visser]</ref>

Sandulova participated in numerous international festivals for [[contemporary classical music|contemporary music]], including <U+201C>ppIANISSIMO<U+201D> in Sofia, Bulgaria and the <U+201C>Buchkunstbiennale<U+201D> in Horn, Austria.<ref>[http://www.cdmc.asso.fr/en/node/2432 ppIANISSIMO <U+2013> International Festival for Contemporary Piano Music]</ref><ref>[http://kunstvereinhorn.jimdo.com/buchkunstbiennale/ Buchkunstbiennale Horn]</ref> She has also delivered international piano master classes and lecture-recitals about Julia Tsenova, among others at the Koyo Conservatory in Kobe, Japan,<ref>[http://www.berklee.edu/international/kobe.html Koyo Conservatory, Kobe, Japan]</ref> the [[Reykjav<U+00ED>k College of Music]] in Iceland and the Staatliche Hochschule f<U+00FC>r Musik und Darstellende Kunst Mannheim, Germany.<ref>[http://www.muho-mannheim.de/ Staatliche Hochschule f<U+00FC>r Musik und Darstellende Kunst Mannheim]</ref>

==Competitions Record==
Sandulova has prizes at the following national and international competitions:
* <U+201C>Liszt-Bartok competition<U+201D>, Sofia, Bulgaria: Honorable mention  (1995).<ref>[http://szofia.balassiintezet.hu/index.php/bg/2012-01-25-08-48-09/2011/--q-q National Piano Competition <U+201C>Liszt-Bartok<U+201D> (Bulgarian)]</ref>

* <U+201C>Music and Earth competition<U+201D>, Sofia, Bulgaria: Piano Duo Performance, awarded by Julia Ganeva and Konstantin Ganev (1996).<ref>[http://www.musicandearth.org/en/ International Competition for Instrumentalists and Composers <U+201C>Music and Earth<U+201D>]</ref>

* <U+201C>Music and Earth competition<U+201D>, Sofia, Bulgaria: Award for Artistic Merit  (1997).

==Premiere performances==
Sandulova has performed Bulgarian, Dutch and world [[premiere]] works of the following composers:
* [[Julia Tsenova]] (Bulgaria)
* Atanas Kosev (Bulgaria) 
* Andre Hamel (Canada)<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/emc/andre-hamel Andr<U+00E9> Hamel on The Canadian Encyclopedia]</ref>
* Rumen Baliozov (Bulgaria) 
* Dimitar Christov (Bulgaria) 
* [[:fr:Marzena Komsta|Marzena Komsta]] (Poland)
* Tsveta Dimitrova (Bulgaria) 
* Petar Petrov (Bulgaria) 
* Vykintas Baltakas (Lithuania)<ref>[http://www.baltakas.net/ Homepage of Vykintas Baltakas]</ref>
* James Mobberley (USA)<ref>[http://www.oberlin.edu/con/bkstage/200102/mobberley/mobberley_james_bio.html James Mobberley, Oberlin College of Arts and Sciences & Conservatory of Music]</ref>
* Lazar Nivolov (Bulgaria) 
* Dimitar Kirov (Bulgaria) 
* Oscar Carmona (Chile)<ref>[http://www.ocarmona.scd.cl/ Homepage of Oscar Carmona]</ref>

